ware.\n\n![Framer 3.0: AI Agents, Branching & What It Means](/images/blog/framer-3-ai-agents.svg)\n\n### Framer 3.0: AI Agents, Branching & What It Means\n\nFramer 3.0 launched June 16, 2026 and reframes Framer as an AI-powered website workspace. This guide breaks down the canvas AI Agents, Git-style branching, external agents via MCP (Claude Code, Cursor, Codex), the redesigned community and marketplace, current pricing, and the honest answer to when Framer is the right choice versus a custom build.\n\n![Open-Weight AI Models Compared: What to Choose When](/images/blog/open-weight-ai-models-comparison.svg)\n\n### Open-Weight AI Models Compared: What to Choose When\n\nGLM 5.2, DeepSeek V4, MiniMax M3, Kimi, and Qwen 3.6 are all MIT or Apache licensed and priced a fraction of the closed frontier. The hard part is picking the right one. This June 2026 guide compares them on intelligence, cost, context, licensing, and multimodality, then gives you a clear decision framework for what to choose when.\n\n![AI for MSPs & ITAD: Win More Clients in the AI Era](/images/blog/ai-for-msp-itad-win-clients.svg)\n\n### AI for MSPs & ITAD: Win More Clients in the AI Era\n\nManaged services is a $380B market and ITAD is heading toward $40B, but competition and the technician shortage are squeezing margins. This playbook shows MSPs and ITAD businesses where AI actually wins: ticket triage, RMM orchestration, device grading, data sanitization, resale optimization, and how to turn it all into a client-winning differentiator.\n\n![AI & GPU Server Decommissioning: 2026 ITAD Growth Playbook](/images/blog/ai-gpu-server-decommissioning-itad.svg)\n\n### AI & GPU Server Decommissioning: 2026 ITAD Growth Playbook\n\nThe AI buildout that filled data centers with GPU clusters is about to run in reverse. With GPU useful life of 3 to 5 years and each H100 worth ~$30,000, a wave of high-value AI hardware is reaching end of life. This playbook shows ITAD providers and MSPs where the margin is, why NIST 800-88 Rev 2 raised the compliance bar, and the AI software that captures the value.\n\n![Loop Engineering and the Future of Software Development](/images/blog/loop-engineering-future-software-dev.svg)\n\n### Loop Engineering and the Future of Software Development\n\nLoop engineering is moving software work from typing prompts to designing the systems that drive AI agents - and it is already reshaping how teams build. With 80% of Anthropic's code and 75% of Google's now AI-authored, and the length of tasks agents can finish doubling every 7 months, here is what loop engineering changes today, what breaks, and where the discipline is headed by 2030.\n\n![GLM 5.2 Developer Guide: 1M Context, MoE & Coding Plan](/images/blog/glm-5-2-developer-guide.svg)\n\n### GLM 5.2 Developer Guide: 1M Context, MoE & Coding Plan\n\nZ.ai's GLM 5.2 (June 13, 2026) is an open-weight, coding-first MoE model with a usable 1M-token context window, a dual thinking-effort system, and 131K output tokens - shipped with zero published benchmarks. This guide covers the architecture, context window, access tiers, and how it stacks up against the closed frontier.\n\n![GLM 5.2 vs Claude Opus 4.8 vs GPT-5.5 for Coding](/images/blog/glm-5-2-vs-claude-gpt.svg)\n\n### GLM 5.2 vs Claude Opus 4.8 vs GPT-5.5 for Coding\n\nGLM 5.2 is open-weight, MIT-licensed, and roughly 5x to 8x cheaper on output tokens than Claude Opus 4.8, with a 1M context window that matches the longest closed models. We compare cost, licensing, context, agentic fit, and what the missing GLM 5.2 benchmarks mean for your decision.\n\n![GLM 5.2 API & Pricing: The GLM Coding Plan Guide](/images/blog/glm-5-2-api-pricing.svg)\n\n### GLM 5.2 API & Pricing: The GLM Coding Plan Guide\n\nGLM 5.2 is one of the cheapest ways to use a frontier-class coding model. This guide breaks down the GLM Coding Plan tiers (Lite ~$3, Pro ~$15, Max ~$80), the rate limits that constrain heavy users, expected API pricing, and how it compares to Claude Code and GitHub Copilot.\n\n![Self-Hosting GLM 5.2: Open Weights, vLLM & VRAM Guide](/images/blog/glm-5-2-self-hosting.svg)\n\n### Self-Hosting GLM 5.2: Open Weights, vLLM & VRAM Guide\n\nGLM 5.2's MIT-licensed open weights let you run a frontier coding model on your own GPUs. This preparation playbook covers the VRAM budget formula, weights memory by precision (~744 GB at FP8), KV cache for 1M context, GPU sizing, vLLM vs SGLang, and the self-host vs API break-even.\n\n![GLM 5.2 Agentic Coding: Building on the 1M Context Window](/images/blog/glm-5-2-agentic-workflows.svg)\n\n### GLM 5.2 Agentic Coding: Building on the 1M Context Window\n\nGLM 5.2's usable 1M-token context window changes what coding agents can do: repository-scale refactors, multi-hour long-horizon tasks, and spec-grounded generation without lossy chunking. This guide covers the agent loop, dual thinking-effort routing, large-context vs RAG, and cost control.\n\n![GLM 5.2 vs GLM 5.1: What's New and Should You Upgrade?](/images/blog/glm-5-2-vs-glm-5-1.svg)\n\n### GLM 5.2 vs GLM 5.1: What's New and Should You Upgrade?\n\nGLM 5.2 (June 13) jumps from a ~200K to a usable 1M-token context window and adds a dual thinking-effort system, but launched without the benchmark numbers GLM 5.1 has. This upgrade guide covers the side-by-side changes, the benchmark caveat, an honest upgrade decision, and a migration checklist.\n\n![GLM 5.2 for Enterprise: Open-Weight Frontier AI Done Right](/images/blog/glm-5-2-enterprise.svg)\n\n### GLM 5.2 for Enterprise: Open-Weight Frontier AI Done Right\n\nGLM 5.2's MIT-licensed open weights let enterprises run a frontier coding model entirely inside their own boundary - no data exfiltration, no vendor lock-in, far lower cost. This guide covers data sovereignty, the MIT license, the responsibilities you take on, and a responsible evaluation plan.\n\nPage 1 of 28\n\n### Ship Better Engineering, Every Week\n\nPractical writing on AI agents, cloud architecture, and product teardowns. Read by builders at startups and Fortune 500s.\n\nWe respect your inbox. Read our [privacy policy](/privacy).\n\n## ContactUs\n\n![Logo](/images/logo-dark.png)\n![Logo](/images/logo-light.png)\n\nCrafting digital excellence through innovative solutions and thoughtful design.\n\n### [Our Services](/services/)\n\n### Contact Info\n\n#### Our Address\n\n131 Continental Dr Suite 305  \nNewark, DE 19713 US\n\n#### Phone\n\n#### Email\n\n© 2025 Lushbinary Inc. All rights reserved."}, {"url": "https://www.linkedin.com/posts/subham-kundu-2746b515b_loop-engineering-has-quietly-become-one-of-activity-7472666533853302784-ssik", "title": "Loop Engineering: Beyond Prompt Engineering for AI Coding | Subham Kundu posted on the topic | LinkedIn", "content": "In simple terms, loop engineering means designing the feedback ... https://lushbinary.com/blog/loop-engineering-ai-coding-agents-guide/ 3.", "score": 0.70287734, "raw_content": "## LinkedIn respects your privacy\n\nLinkedIn and 3rd parties use essential and non-essential cookies to provide, secure, analyze and improve our Services, and to show you relevant ads (including **professional and job ads**) on and off LinkedIn. Learn more in our [Cookie Policy](https://www.linkedin.com/legal/cookie-policy).\n\nSelect Accept to consent or Reject to decline non-essential cookies for this use. You can update your choices at any time in your [settings](https://www.linkedin.com/mypreferences/g/guest-cookies).\n\nAgree & Join LinkedIn\n\nBy clicking Continue to join or sign in, you agree to LinkedIn’s [User Agreement](/legal/user-agreement?trk=linkedin-tc_auth-button_user-agreement), [Privacy Policy](/legal/privacy-policy?trk=linkedin-tc_auth-button_privacy-policy), and [Cookie Policy](/legal/cookie-policy?trk=linkedin-tc_auth-button_cookie-policy).\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n![]()\n\n# Loop Engineering: Beyond Prompt Engineering for AI Coding\n\n![View profile for Subham Kundu]()\n\nLoop engineering has quietly become one of the hottest topics in the AI coding ecosystem, yet most teams still treat their agents like one-shot code generators. After applying these workflows for a few clients, here's why the loop matters more than the prompt.\nIn simple terms, loop engineering means designing the feedback cycle around an agent, not just its input. Instead of asking a model to produce code once, you build a system: the agent gathers context, makes a small change, runs validation, reads the outcome, and adjusts until the work is verified or blocked. Prompt engineering shapes the first answer. Loop engineering shapes the final one.\nThis matters because a strong first answer is rarely a correct final change. The real signal appears after the first action: a failing test, a broken type check, a reviewer catching an edge case.\nThree failure modes show up repeatedly in client work.\nChallenge 1: Thrashing. The agent changes code without converging. I fix this by narrowing the objective and forcing small, reversible diffs.\nChallenge 2: Overfitting to tests. The agent passes tests but misses the requirement. The fix is pairing tests with requirement review and browser checks.\nChallenge 3: Context drift. The agent works from stale assumptions. I refresh context after every meaningful observation.\nPersonally, I believe the key skill ahead won't be writing the perfect prompt, but designing reliable loops of context, action, observation, and correction.\nYou can learn more about loop engineering at : [Resources in the 1st comment]\n\n\n![]()\n![]()\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n![Subham Kundu, graphic]()\n\n1. [https://www.mindstudio.ai/blog/what-is-loop-engineering-ai-coding-agents](https://www.mindstudio.ai/blog/what-is-loop-engineering-ai-coding-agents?trk=public_post_comment-text)\n2. [https://lushbinary.com/blog/loop-engineering-ai-coding-agents-guide](https://lushbinary.com/blog/loop-engineering-ai-coding-agents-guide?trk=public_post_comment-text)/\n3. [https://www.louisbouchard.ai/loop-engineering](https://www.louisbouchard.ai/loop-engineering?trk=public_post_comment-text)/\n\n![Labeeb Ismail, graphic]()\n\nThe problem is sub-optimal point solutions that gets merged into code without anyone detecting those and the entropy of the code steadily increasing.\nThere has to be specific outer loops which heavily criticizes solutions from the inner loops with a larger view of the codebase. I have incorporated this using Kavia’s Knowledge framework.\n\n![Georgios Diamantopoulos PhD, graphic]()\n\nJust slap on \"engineering\" to any thing and it IMMEDIATELY becomes legit. It's no longer \"engineering <thing>\" - \"<thing> engineering\" takes you from zero to consultant.\n\nTo view or add a comment, [sign in](https://www.linkedin.com/signup/cold-join?session_redirect=https%3A%2F%2Fwww%2Elinkedin%2Ecom%2Fposts%2Fsubham-kundu-2746b515b_loop-engineering-has-quietly-become-one-of-activity-7472666533853302784-ssik&trk=public_post_feed-cta-banner-cta)\n\n## More Relevant Posts\n\n![View profile for Pierre de Lacaze]()\n\nCode as Agent Harness (University of Illinois Urbana-Champaign , May 72026, 102 pages)\nPaper: [https://lnkd.in/esmnFnnZ](https://www.linkedin.com/redir/redirect?url=https%3A%2F%2Flnkd%2Ein%2FesmnFnnZ&urlhash=UGDq&trk=public_post-text)\nAbstract:\n\"Recent large language models (LLMs) have demonstrated strong capabilities in understanding and generating code, from competitive programming to repository-level software engineering. In emerging agentic systems, code is no longer only a target output. It increasingly serves as an operational substrate for agent reasoning, acting, environment modeling, and execution-based verification. We frame this shift through the lens of agent harnesses and introduce code as agent harness: a unified view that centers code as the basis for agent infrastructure. To systematically study this perspective, we organize the survey around three connected layers. First, we study the harness interface, where code connects agents to reasoning, action, and environment modeling. Second, we examine harness mechanisms: planning, memory, and tool use for long-horizon execution, together with feedback-driven control and optimization that make harness reliable and adaptive. Third, we discuss scaling the harness from single-agent systems to multi-agent settings, where shared code artifacts support multi-agent coordination, review, and verification. Across these layers, we summarize representative methods and practical applications of code as agent harness, spanning coding assistants, GUI/OS automation, embodied agents, scientific discovery, personalization and recommendation, DevOps, and enterprise workflows. We further outline open challenges for harness engineering, including evaluation beyond final task success, verification under incomplete feedback, regression-free harness improvement, consistent shared state across multiple agents, human oversight for safety-critical actions, and extensions to multimodal environments. By centering code as the harness of agentic AI, this survey provides a unified roadmap toward executable, verifiable, and stateful AI agent systems.\"\n\n![No alternative text description for this image]()\n\n\n![]()\n![]()\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\nTo view or add a comment, [sign in](https://www.linkedin.com/signup/cold-join?session_redirect=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.linkedin.com%2Fposts%2Fpierre-de-lacaze-b11026b_code-as-agent-harness-university-of-illinois-activity-7462735084559794176-eAoc&trk=public_post_feed-cta-banner-cta)\n\n![View profile for Girish Rengaswamy]()\n\nArchitected Vibes: Why AI Coding Needs Structure\nInside modern engineering teams, I’m seeing a growing divide between two developer mindsets.\nThe first is the Vibe Coder - developers moving at incredible speed with AI, shipping features in days instead of weeks. They operate in YOLO mode - “You Only Look/Live Once.” The focus is momentum, experimentation, and getting things working fast.\nAnd honestly, it works… at first.\nBut after a few months, many of these projects hit what we call the 3-Month Wall. The codebase becomes difficult to maintain, architecture starts drifting, tests are incomplete, and nobody fully understands the AI-generated abstractions anymore.\nOn the other side are structured engineering teams focused on:\n- Spec-Driven Development (SDD)\n- Test-Driven Development (TDD)\n- Documentation\n- Architecture reviews\nThe challenge is that traditional workflows often feel too slow in an AI-first world.\nThat’s why I believe the future is not pure vibe coding or rigid process-heavy engineering.\nThe future is Architected Vibes.\nA workflow where AI speed is combined with engineering discipline. Where specifications, contracts, and tests are generated first, forcing AI-generated code to align with clear expectations before merge.\nAI can generate code faster than ever.\nBut sustainable engineering still requires structure, shared understanding, and systems that generate trust - not just velocity.\n\n![No alternative text description for this image]()\n![]()\n\n\n![]()\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\nTo view or add a comment, [sign in](https://www.linkedin.com/signup/cold-join?session_redirect=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.linkedin.com%2Fposts%2Fgirishra_architected-vibes-why-ai-coding-needs-structure-activity-7462475472665354240-1SBw&trk=public_post_feed-cta-banner-cta)\n\n![View profile for Ruben Bertelo]()\n\nFollow-up to on LLM coding costs — here's the technique side.\n[Addy Osmani](https://www.linkedin.com/in/addyosmani?trk=public_post-text) \"Loop Engineering\": stop prompting agents one turn at a time, and design the \\*system\\* that prompts them. [Boris Cherny](https://www.linkedin.com/in/bcherny?trk=public_post-text) (head of Claude Code) says his job now is writing loops, not prompting Claude.\nThe shape, now native in both Claude Code and Codex: automations that find work, isolated worktrees for parallel agents, skills that store project context, connectors into your real tools, and sub-agents where one writes and another checks — plus memory that lives outside the conversation.\nThe caveats are the point, not an afterthought: verification's still on you, your understanding rots if you stop reading the code, and it's tempting to just rubber-stamp whatever the loop returns.\nTies straight back to the cost question — are sub-agent loops the token-heavy pattern that gets expensive fast?\nAnyone actually building loops yet? Curious whether it's living up to the hype — and what it's doing to your token bill.\n[https://lnkd.in/dcyC8-Tw](https://www.linkedin.com/redir/redirect?url=https%3A%2F%2Flnkd%2Ein%2FdcyC8-Tw&urlhash=GkTJ&trk=public_post-text)\n[#AI](https://www.linkedin.com/signup/cold-join?session_redirect=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.linkedin.com%2Ffeed%2Fhashtag%2Fai&trk=public_post-text) [#LLM](https://www.linkedin.com/signup/cold-join?session_redirect=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.linkedin.com%2Ffeed%2Fhashtag%2Fllm&trk=public_post-text) [#ClaudeCode](https://www.linkedin.com/signup/cold-join?session_redirect=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.linkedin.com%2Ffeed%2Fhashtag%2Fclaudecode&trk=public_post-text) [#AgenticAI](https://www.linkedin.com/signup/cold-join?session_redirect=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.linkedin.com%2Ffeed%2Fhashtag%2Fagenticai&trk=public_post-text)\n\n![Loop Engineering]()\n\n\n![]()\n![]()\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\nTo view or add a comment, [sign in](https://www.linkedin.com/signup/cold-join?session_redirect=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.linkedin.com%2Fposts%2Frubenbertelo_loop-engineering-activity-7470036784844906501-regM&trk=public_post_feed-cta-banner-cta)\n\n![View profile for María Dolz García]()\n\nRecently, I attended the course Introduction to Agent Skills by Anthropic Academy and learnt about Claude Skills, [CLAUDE.md](https://www.linkedin.com/redir/redirect?url=http%3A%2F%2FCLAUDE%2Emd&urlhash=onXc&trk=public_post-text) files, hooks and subagents. I find it fascinating how software development workflows are evolving alongside AI agents.\nThis led me to explore a recent study that analysed 328 [CLAUDE.md](https://www.linkedin.com/redir/redirect?url=http%3A%2F%2FCLAUDE%2Emd&urlhash=onXc&trk=public_post-text) configuration files used to guide AI coding agents: [https://lnkd.in/edymn7GM](https://www.linkedin.com/redir/redirect?url=https%3A%2F%2Flnkd%2Ein%2Fedymn7GM&urlhash=gAWs&trk=public_post-text)\nOne of the findings that particularly caught my attention is that the most common configuration pattern combines Architecture, Dependencies and Project Overview, while Architecture appears in all of the top five patterns.\nIt was interesting to see that, even in agent-driven development, many of the concerns remain familiar software engineering topics: understanding system architecture, managing dependencies, defining development practices and establishing testing guidelines.\n\n![Decoding the Configuration of AI Coding Agents: Insights from Claude Code Projects]()\n\n\n![]()\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\nTo view or add a comment, [sign in](https://www.linkedin.com/signup/cold-join?session_redirect=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.linkedin.com%2Fposts%2Fmar%25C3%25ADa-dolz-garc%25C3%25ADa-_decoding-the-configuration-of-ai-coding-agents-activity-7470512637093765120-9pgj&trk=public_post_feed-cta-banner-cta)\n\n![View profile for Raj Madhuram]()\n\nEnter Loop Engineering ✨. Vibe coding is so 2025 😅!\nThe term \"Vibe coding\" was coined by Andrej Karpathy in a Feb 2025 tweet, saying, \"it's not really coding - I just see stuff, say stuff, run stuff, and copy paste stuff, and it mostly works.\"\nNext came \"Agentic AI\", a new breed of AI systems that are semi- or fully autonomous and thus able to perceive, reason, and act on their own (MIT definition). Claude Code rules this space, and developers also use Codex and Antigravity. Also btw, my friend [Carsten](https://de.linkedin.com/in/carstenlawrenz?trk=public_post-text) has been building a very cool harness for agents called C10:OS. I'll write more about it soon.\nIn the last few days, I've been hearing more and more about \"Loop Engineering\". Addy Osmani defines it as \"Loop engineering is replacing yourself as the person who prompts the agent. You design the system that does it instead.\" - very meta, isn't it? Read his essay here: [https://lnkd.in/gU2gMrKh](https://www.linkedin.com/redir/redirect?url=https%3A%2F%2Flnkd%2Ein%2FgU2gMrKh&urlhash=l7gY&trk=public_post-text)\nI have mixed feelings about these approaches. I definitely see the uses of Agentic AI. For people without any programming background who want to build software, this is a godsend! However, if you have built a solid engineering team with established best practices, the narrative I often hear is that it no longer matters. I strongly disagree with this. There are certain classes of software in which Agentic works well, but I have observed that beyond a certain level of complexity, it breaks down.\nWhen I said \"complexity,\" it was a loose term for Entropy, as in information theory. I was recently thinking a lot about how to measure software specification complexity (as these are the input for Agents). I came across this excellent paper on Software Entropy: [https://lnkd.in/gQmcCjNS](https://www.linkedin.com/redir/redirect?url=https%3A%2F%2Flnkd%2Ein%2FgQmcCjNS&urlhash=FIjV&trk=public_post-text)\nMy theory is that if you are crafting or dealing with complex software, the product surface is a fractal (think of a huge mind map), and, as a result, the software entropy increases significantly.  No matter how meta you get, there is no escape from this complexity!\n\n![No alternative text description for this image]()\n\n\n![]()\n![]()\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\nTo view or add a comment, [sign in](https://www.linkedin.com/signup/cold-join?session_redirect=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.linkedin.com%2Fposts%2Frmadhuram_enter-loop-engineering-vibe-coding-is-activity-7470434675598094337-rs-n&trk=public_post_feed-cta-banner-cta)\n\n![View profile for Lavanya Dandona]()\n\nAnthropic says Claude wrote 80% of its production code in May.\nPublished June 4, Anthropic shared that Claude now handles the majority of production code at the company. Engineers are merging 8x more code per day compared to 2024. Claude's success rate on open-ended coding tasks has jumped 50 percentage points in six months.\nMost of the coverage is treating this as a story about software engineering.\nIt is a story about every knowledge worker's job in the next three years.\nHere's what actually shifted: the bottleneck moved from creation to review and direction.\nWhen Claude can produce more code than engineers used to write manually, engineers don't become redundant. They become directors. Their job is to evaluate what was produced, identify what's wrong, and decide what comes next.\nThe same shift is already beginning in content, design, and marketing.\nWhen an AI agent can produce 10 post variations in the time it used to take to write one, the question isn't \"can I keep up with this volume?\" It's \"do I have the judgment to evaluate which one is right and why?\"\nProduction capacity is compressing. Directional judgment is not.\nThat's the skill worth sharpening right now.\n\n\n![]()\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\nTo view or add a comment, [sign in](https://www.linkedin.com/signup/cold-join?session_redirect=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.linkedin.com%2Fposts%2Flavanyadandona_anthropic-says-claude-wrote-80-of-its-production-activity-7470135223339610112-I31L&trk=public_post_feed-cta-banner-cta)\n\n![View profile for Dr. rer. nat. Varun Kapoor]()\n\nSo what do we think about usage of AI tools in Coding, It must be our enemy right, given that we are primarily a scientific software and consulting provider company so how are we doing and thinking about it? Read it here: [https://lnkd.in/e-6srQy5](https://www.linkedin.com/redir/redirect?url=https%3A%2F%2Flnkd%2Ein%2Fe-6srQy5&urlhash=QUrl&trk=public_post-text)\n\n![AI Is the Construction Worker. You Are Still the Architect.]()\n\n\n![]()\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\nTo view or add a comment, [sign in](https://www.linkedin.com/signup/cold-join?session_redirect=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.linkedin.com%2Fposts%2Fdr-rer-nat-varun-kapoor-6734b982_ai-is-the-construction-worker-you-are-still-activity-7467179396865507328-BCLn&trk=public_post_feed-cta-banner-cta)\n\n![View organization page for AlphaSignal]()\n\n87,009 followers\n\nA new AI engineering philosophy flips how every codebase gets built.\nMost codebases get harder to work with every year.\nEach new feature is a negotiation with the old ones.\nTeams end up fighting their system instead of building on it.\nEvery just open-sourced a plugin that flips this.\nIt's called Compound Engineering, and ships for Claude Code, Codex, and Cursor.\nThe core idea is simple. Each unit of work makes the next one easier.\nBug fixes eliminate entire categories of future bugs. Codified patterns become reusable tools.\nThe system runs on a four-step loop:\n1. Plan changes with parallel research agents\n2. Work inside an isolated git worktree\n3. Review using 14 specialists in parallel\n4. Compound the lesson into searchable docs\nEngineers spend 80% of their time planning and reviewing.\nOne command chains the full pipeline. It spawns over 50 agents from start to finish.\nLink in comments.\n↓\nCheck out [https://lnkd.in/eXz8ge-e](https://www.linkedin.com/redir/redirect?url=https%3A%2F%2Flnkd%2Ein%2FeXz8ge-e&urlhash=ymvR&trk=public_post-text) to get a daily summary of the latest\nbreakthrough news, models, papers and repos. Read by 300,000+ devs.\n\n![No alternative text description for this image]()\n\n\n![]()\n![]()\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\nTo view or add a comment, [sign in](https://www.linkedin.com/signup/cold-join?session_redirect=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.linkedin.com%2Fposts%2Falphasignal_a-new-ai-engineering-philosophy-flips-how-activity-7468633348496572416-yoXt&trk=public_post_feed-cta-banner-cta)\n\n![View profile for Akash Agnihotri]()\n\nWe now have a new level of abstraction in programming, and with it a lot of old ways are in question. The goal has not changed though. It cannot. Quality is non-negotiable.\nSo as engineering leads, what are the new tools and ways of working we must adopt to enforce the age old principles that delivered the production grade applications of the past?\nIn this post I talk about real-world examples of how teams can keep using agentic tools like Claude Code while holding the same high engineering standards.\n\n![Leading AI Native Engineering Teams]()\n\n\n![]()\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\nTo view or add a comment, [sign in](https://www.linkedin.com/signup/cold-join?session_redirect=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.linkedin.com%2Fposts%2Fagni25_leading-ai-native-engineering-teams-activity-7466137477767069696-yfr4&trk=public_post_feed-cta-banner-cta)\n\n![View profile for Maxime DEHAUT]()\n\nA recurring question in my team this year: how do you move from calling an LLM to actually engineering an agent? Most resources either stay too abstract or jump straight to framework tutorials. With ±80% of organisations now deploying agent-based systems at some level, the gap between \"we're experimenting\" and \"we have something production-worthy\" is where most teams are stuck. Source: 𝙰̲𝚛̲𝚌̲𝚊̲𝚍̲𝚎̲ 𝙱̲𝚕̲𝚘̲𝚐̲\n𝐀𝐈 𝐀𝐠𝐞𝐧𝐭𝐬 𝐢𝐧 𝐀𝐜𝐭𝐢𝐨𝐧 by [Micheal Lanham](https://ca.linkedin.com/in/micheal-lanham-189693123?trk=public_post-text) ( [Manning Publications Co.](https://www.linkedin.com/company/manning-publications-co?trk=public_post-text)) is a hands-on guide to closing that gap — from first principles through multi-agent orchestration and deployment.\nWhat I like about this book is its architectural honesty. It covers memory properly: RAG, vector similarity search, document embeddings, and the distinction between semantic, episodic, and procedural memory stores. It also covers a very interesting concept: behaviour trees as an orchestration mechanism — a structural approach borrowed from robotics.\n   𝐀𝐆𝐄𝐍𝐓 𝐑𝐄𝐋𝐈𝐀𝐁𝐈𝐋𝐈𝐓𝐘\n      𝐂𝐎𝐌𝐄𝐒 𝐅𝐑𝐎𝐌 𝐀𝐑𝐂𝐇𝐈𝐓𝐄𝐂𝐓𝐔𝐑𝐄,\n      𝐍𝐎𝐓 𝐅𝐑𝐎𝐌 𝐁𝐄𝐓𝐓𝐄𝐑 𝐏𝐑𝐎𝐌𝐏𝐓𝐒.\n𝐖𝐡𝐨 𝐢𝐭'𝐬 𝐟𝐨𝐫 / 𝐰𝐡𝐨 𝐢𝐭'𝐬 𝐧𝐨𝐭 𝐟𝐨𝐫\n👉 𝐅𝐨𝐫: Intermediate Python developers and technical leads building or evaluating agent systems who want engineering rigour, not just API recipes.\n✋ 𝐍𝐨𝐭 𝐟𝐨𝐫: Those working outside the OpenAI/Python ecosystem, or architects seeking language-agnostic design patterns.\n🔗Links:\n- Book: [https://lnkd.in/dgkEaXjq](https://www.linkedin.com/redir/redirect?url=https%3A%2F%2Flnkd%2Ein%2FdgkEaXjq&urlhash=UsD8&trk=public_post-text)\n- Arcade Blog: [https://lnkd.in/dM\\_qFaud](https://www.linkedin.com/redir/redirect?url=https%3A%2F%2Flnkd%2Ein%2FdM_qFaud&urlhash=osuz&trk=public_post-text)\n\n\n![]()\n![]()\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\nTo view or add a comment, [sign in](https://www.linkedin.com/signup/cold-join?session_redirect=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.linkedin.com%2Fposts%2Fmaxime-dehaut-5509b233_a-recurring-question-in-my-team-this-year-activity-7464585793391685632-4mmc&trk=public_post_feed-cta-banner-cta)\n\n![](https://media.licdn.com/dms/image/v2/D4E16AQEgBxo46BegHQ/profile-displaybackgroundimage-shrink_200_800/B4EZ5n.3cqI0AU-/0/1779860994382?e=2147483647&v=beta&t=TjXpsphgSkaeab1Njbip2rbjXVOIIE65vtjn7bgvXTU)\n![Subham Kundu]()\n\n18,227 followers\n\n## More from this author\n\n![]()\n\n### From Brain to Bot: How the AMCC Could Revolutionise LLM Training\n\n## Explore content categories\n\n![]()\n\n## Sign in to view more content\n\nCreate your free account or sign in to continue your search\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\nor\n\nNew to LinkedIn? [Join now](https://www.linkedin.com/signup/cold-join?session_redirect=https%3A%2F%2Fwww%2Elinkedin%2Ecom%2Fposts%2Fsubham-kundu-2746b515b_loop-engineering-has-quietly-become-one-of-activity-7472666533853302784-ssik&trk=public_post_contextual-sign-in-modal_join-link)\n\nBy clicking Continue to join or sign in, you agree to LinkedIn’s [User Agreement](/legal/user-agreement?trk=linkedin-tc_auth-button_user-agreement), [Privacy Policy](/legal/privacy-policy?trk=linkedin-tc_auth-button_privacy-policy), and [Cookie Policy](/legal/cookie-policy?trk=linkedin-tc_auth-button_cookie-policy)."}, {"url": "https://linas.substack.com/p/loop-engineering-complete-guide", "title": "Design AI Loops That Ship While You Sleep - Linas's Newsletter", "content": "# Loop Engineering: Design AI Loops That Ship While You Sleep. [![Image 1: Linas's Newsletter](https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/$s_!CIl4!,w_40,h_40,c_fill,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fbucketeer-e05bbc84-baa3-437e-9518-adb32be77984.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F54b1f35a-f4b2-43de-bde7-e5f777b4a766_500x500.png)](https://linas.substack.com/). # [Linas's Newsletter](https://linas.substack.com/). # Loop Engineering: How to Design AI Loops That Build, Ship, and Improve While You Sleep 🔁. [![Image 2: Linas Beliūnas's avatar](https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/$s_!rK9I!,w_36,h_36,c_fill,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fbucketeer-e05bbc84-baa3-437e-9518-adb32be77984.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F49315514-410c-4df5-a878-9421b6671e50_1280x853.jpeg)](https://substack.com/@linas). [Linas Beliūnas](https://substack.com/@linas). On June 7, 2026, Peter Steinberger - the creator of **[OpenClaw](https://linas.substack.com/p/firstonepersonunicorn)**[, the open-source AI agent project that became the most-starred new repo in GitHub history](https://linas.substack.com/p/firstonepersonunicorn) - posted twelve words that broke the entire AI-coding internet:. You should be designing loops that prompt your agents.”_. [![Image 3](https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/$s_!uFh6!,w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fdc3f5248-1861-4031-aed3-8031beb3ff0d_1320x783.jpeg)](https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/$s_!uFh6!,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fdc3f5248-1861-4031-aed3-8031beb3ff0d_1320x783.jpeg). Boris Cherny, the Creator & Head of Claude Code at **[Anthropic](https://linas.substack.com/p/anthropic-claude-2026-every-launch-guide)**, said the same thing on stage a few days before:. ###### Source: [Boris Cherny: Claude Code & the Future of Engineering | Acquired Unplugged presented by WorkOS.](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=RkQQ7WEor7w). *   **Designing loops with****Claude Fable 5**, Anthropic’s newest frontier AI model built from the ground up for long-horizon agentic autonomy. ## What Is a Loop? [Subscribe](https://linas.substack.com/subscribe?simple=true&next=https%3A%2F%2Flinas.substack.com%2Fp%2Floop-engineering-complete-guide%3Futm_source%3Dsubstack%26utm_medium%3Demail&utm_source=paywall&utm_medium=web&utm_content=201415611). **Sign in**](https://substack.com/sign-in?redirect=%2Fp%2Floop-engineering-complete-guide%3Futm_source%3Dsubstack%26utm_medium%3Demail&for_pub=linas&change_user=false). [Start your Substack](https://substack.com/signup?utm_source=substack&utm_medium=web&utm_content=footer)[Get the app](https://substack.com/app/app-store-redirect?utm_campaign=app-marketing&utm_content=web-footer-button).", "score": 0.375043, "raw_content": "# Loop Engineering: Design AI Loops That Ship While You Sleep\n\n[![Image 1: Linas's Newsletter](https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/$s_!CIl4!,w_40,h_40,c_fill,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fbucketeer-e05bbc84-baa3-437e-9518-adb32be77984.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F54b1f35a-f4b2-43de-bde7-e5f777b4a766_500x500.png)](https://linas.substack.com/)\n\n# [Linas's Newsletter](https://linas.substack.com/)\n\nSubscribe Sign in\n\n# Loop Engineering: How to Design AI Loops That Build, Ship, and Improve While You Sleep 🔁\n\n### From a three-line bash script to multi-day Claude Fable 5 autonomy — everything founders, builders, and investors need to stop prompting agents and start designing the systems that prompt them.\n\n[![Image 2: Linas Beliūnas's avatar](https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/$s_!rK9I!,w_36,h_36,c_fill,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fbucketeer-e05bbc84-baa3-437e-9518-adb32be77984.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F49315514-410c-4df5-a878-9421b6671e50_1280x853.jpeg)](https://substack.com/@linas)\n\n[Linas Beliūnas](https://substack.com/@linas)\n\nJun 10, 2026\n\n∙ Paid\n\n48\n\n9\n\nShare\n\n👋 _Hey, Linas here! Every day, I break down 3 stories shaping the future of FinTech & Artificial Intelligence - plus the money movements and trends worth tracking. First time here? 390k+ FinTech and AI leaders get this daily. Join them:_\n\nSubscribe\n\nOn June 7, 2026, Peter Steinberger - the creator of **[OpenClaw](https://linas.substack.com/p/firstonepersonunicorn)**[, the open-source AI agent project that became the most-starred new repo in GitHub history](https://linas.substack.com/p/firstonepersonunicorn) - posted twelve words that broke the entire AI-coding internet:\n\n_“You shouldn’t be prompting coding agents anymore. You should be designing loops that prompt your agents.”_\n\n[![Image 3](https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/$s_!uFh6!,w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fdc3f5248-1861-4031-aed3-8031beb3ff0d_1320x783.jpeg)](https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/$s_!uFh6!,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fdc3f5248-1861-4031-aed3-8031beb3ff0d_1320x783.jpeg)\n\nBoris Cherny, the Creator & Head of Claude Code at **[Anthropic](https://linas.substack.com/p/anthropic-claude-2026-every-launch-guide)**, said the same thing on stage a few days before:\n\n_“I don’t prompt Claude anymore. I have loops running. They’re the ones prompting Claude and figuring out what to do. My job is to write loops.”_\n\n###### Source: [Boris Cherny: Claude Code & the Future of Engineering | Acquired Unplugged presented by WorkOS.](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=RkQQ7WEor7w)\n\nTwo statements. Millions of views. And a wave of confusion, because almost nobody could define what a **loop** actually _was_.\n\nThis guide was written to answer this completely. And it’s not _just_ for engineers, but also for **the founders trying to ship faster** with a team of two, **the****investors trying to evaluate** which AI-native companies are building durable advantages, and **the operators trying to understand** why their competitors seem to be moving at a different speed.\n\nWhat you’ll find inside:\n\n*   **Where loops came from** and how they actually work\n\n*   **The full anatomy of a loop** and how to build one in under ten minutes\n\n*   **The 14-step roadmap** from manual prompter to loop engineer\n\n*   **A practical catalog of 41 pre-built loops** ready to copy-paste today\n\n*   **Designing loops with****Claude Fable 5**, Anthropic’s newest frontier AI model built from the ground up for long-horizon agentic autonomy\n\n*   **Where loops fail, what they cost**, and the three debts that get worse the better they work.\n\nThe leverage point has now clearly moved. Prompting was last year. This is what’s next, and it is available for everyone right now.\n\n## What Is a Loop?\n\n## This post is for paid subscribers\n\n[Subscribe](https://linas.substack.com/subscribe?simple=true&next=https%3A%2F%2Flinas.substack.com%2Fp%2Floop-engineering-complete-guide%3Futm_source%3Dsubstack%26utm_medium%3Demail&utm_source=paywall&utm_medium=web&utm_content=201415611)\n\n[Already a paid subscriber? **Sign in**](https://substack.com/sign-in?redirect=%2Fp%2Floop-engineering-complete-guide%3Futm_source%3Dsubstack%26utm_medium%3Demail&for_pub=linas&change_user=false)\n\n© 2026 Linas Beliūnas · [Privacy](https://substack.com/privacy) ∙ [Terms](https://substack.com/tos) ∙ [Collection notice](https://substack.com/ccpa#personal-data-collected)\n\n[Start your Substack](https://substack.com/signup?utm_source=substack&utm_medium=web&utm_content=footer)[Get the app](https://substack.com/app/app-store-redirect?utm_campaign=app-marketing&utm_content=web-footer-button)\n\n[Substack](https://substack.com/) is the home for great culture"}, {"url": "https://kilo.ai/articles/what-is-loop-engineering", "title": "What Is Loop Engineering? AI Feedback Loops | Kilo", "content": "Learn what loop engineering means, how AI coding feedback loops work, and how teams can use iterative agent workflows to ship better software. Loop engineering is the practice of designing, operating, and improving the feedback loops that let AI coding agents plan work, change code, observe results, and revise their approach until a software task is complete. Instead of treating an AI tool as a one-shot code generator, loop engineering treats software work as an iterative system: define the goal, inspect the codebase, make a change, run validation, read the outcome, and decide what to do next. Loop engineering is the practice of designing AI-assisted workflows where an agent repeatedly plans, acts, observes feedback, and adjusts until a software task is complete or blocked. ### Why does loop engineering matter for AI coding agents? A common coding loop is: inspect the relevant files, make a small change, run a targeted test, read the failure or success output, adjust the code, and repeat until the task passes validation.", "score": 0.34713915, "raw_content": "[Sign in](/api/impact/redirect?target=https%3A%2F%2Fapp.kilo.ai%2Fusers%2Fsign_in)[Sign up](/api/impact/redirect?target=https%3A%2F%2Fapp.kilo.ai%2Fusers%2Fsign_in)\n\n\n\n# What Is Loop Engineering?\n\nLearn what loop engineering means, how AI coding feedback loops work, and how teams can use iterative agent workflows to ship better software.\n\n[Arkadiy Kondrashov](https://www.linkedin.com/in/arkadiy-kondrashov/)\n\nGrowth Marketing @ Kilo\n\nPublished\n\nLast Updated\n\nLoop engineering is the practice of designing, operating, and improving the feedback loops that let AI coding agents plan work, change code, observe results, and revise their approach until a software task is complete. Instead of treating an AI tool as a one-shot code generator, loop engineering treats software work as an iterative system: define the goal, inspect the codebase, make a change, run validation, read the outcome, and decide what to do next.\n\nThe concept matters because modern software work is rarely solved by a single prompt. Real projects include hidden constraints, flaky tests, legacy conventions, deployment rules, product tradeoffs, and incomplete requirements. A useful AI coding workflow needs more than a model that can produce plausible code. It needs a loop that turns guesses into verified progress.\n\n## Loop Engineering Fundamentals\n\nLoop engineering is the discipline of structuring AI-assisted software development around repeated cycles of action and feedback. The core idea is simple: the agent should not merely answer once; it should use evidence from the codebase and validation tools to improve its next step.\n\nA basic loop has five stages:\n\n1. **Intent**: the developer or system defines the target outcome.\n2. **Context**: the agent gathers relevant code, documentation, errors, logs, and constraints.\n3. **Action**: the agent edits files, runs commands, calls tools, or drafts a plan.\n4. **Observation**: the system captures test results, compiler errors, runtime output, diffs, review comments, or user feedback.\n5. **Adjustment**: the agent updates its plan and repeats the loop until the work is accepted or blocked.\n\nThis definition separates loop engineering from prompt engineering. Prompt engineering focuses on shaping the input to a model. Loop engineering focuses on shaping the full process around the model: the tools it can use, the context it sees, the validation it trusts, the stopping criteria it follows, and the way humans intervene.\n\nThe distinction matters because a strong first answer is not the same as a correct final change. In production code, the important signal often appears after the first action: a failing type check, a missing import, a broken test, a screenshot that exposes a layout issue, or a reviewer pointing out an edge case. Loop engineering makes those signals part of the system rather than treating them as after-the-fact cleanup.\n\nEarly AI coding tools were mostly autocomplete systems. They helped developers write individual lines or functions faster, while the human remained responsible for understanding the project, finding the right files, running tests, interpreting failures, and deciding the next change. AI coding agents changed that pattern by taking on more of the plan-act-verify cycle. Loop engineering exists because that added autonomy needs structure.\n\n## How The Core Loop Works In AI Coding\n\nThe core AI coding loop turns software development into a sequence of small, observable steps. Most agentic coding workflows can be reduced to this cycle:\n\n1. **Plan**: break the request into concrete steps.\n2. **Search**: find the files, symbols, tests, and conventions that matter.\n3. **Modify**: make the smallest coherent code change.\n4. **Verify**: run type checks, tests, builds, linters, previews, or targeted scripts.\n5. **Repair**: use the verification output to fix mistakes.\n6. **Summarize**: explain what changed, what passed, and what remains risky.\n\nThe power is not in any single step. The power is in closing the loop. A test failure is not just an error message; it is new context. A type error is not just a blocker; it is a signal about an assumption that was wrong. A code review comment is not just feedback; it is another observation that can drive the next action.\n\nFor example, a developer might ask an agent to fix a bug where users cannot save billing settings when the company name contains an apostrophe. A weak loop guesses that the bug is SQL escaping and patches the query. A stronger loop first finds the form, API route, validation schema, and database update path. It reproduces the failure, observes whether the problem is client validation, server validation, serialization, SQL, or display logic, then changes the smallest relevant code path and runs a targeted regression test.\n\nThis is why loop engineering is useful even when the model is highly capable. A capable model can still start from an incomplete assumption. The loop gives it a way to discover that assumption, correct it, and prove the fix before the developer reviews the final diff.\n\nPrompt engineering still plays a role inside the loop. Clear instructions improve the first plan and reduce unnecessary exploration. The difference is that loop engineering assumes the first answer may be incomplete and designs the workflow to improve from there.\n\n| Dimension | Prompt engineering | Loop engineering |\n| --- | --- | --- |\n| Primary unit | A prompt or instruction | A repeated workflow |\n| Goal | Better first response | Better final outcome |\n| Feedback | Usually human evaluation | Tests, tools, diffs, logs, reviews, and humans |\n| Failure mode | The model gives a weak answer | The system loops poorly, stops early, or ignores evidence |\n| Best for | Isolated answers and generation | Real software tasks with uncertainty |\n\n## What Makes A Good AI Engineering Loop\n\nA good AI engineering loop is designed around clear goals, useful context, small actions, reliable observations, and explicit stopping rules. It is not simply \"let the agent keep trying.\" Unbounded retries can waste time, hide bad assumptions, or create unnecessary code churn.\n\n### Clear Objectives\n\nThe loop needs a concrete definition of success. \"Improve the dashboard\" is vague. \"Reduce initial dashboard load time by deferring non-critical charts while keeping existing filters working\" gives the agent something observable to optimize. The second version contains scope, behavior, and a constraint, so it produces a tighter feedback loop.\n\nStrong objectives usually include:\n\n* the desired user-visible behavior\n* files or areas that are likely relevant\n* constraints that must not change\n* validation commands that should pass\n* tradeoffs that are acceptable\n\n### Relevant Context\n\nAgents need the right amount of context. Too little context leads to wrong assumptions. Too much context can drown the model in irrelevant details. Context should explain how the current project works, not merely fill the model window.\n\nUseful context often includes:\n\n* nearby code and existing patterns\n* package scripts and dependency versions\n* failing test output or error traces\n* product requirements and edge cases\n* examples of similar implementations\n* coding standards and repository instructions\n\nThe loop should gather context before editing, then refresh context after important observations.\n\n### Small Reversible Actions\n\nThe best loops favor small, reviewable changes. A small diff is easier to verify and easier to repair. Large speculative rewrites make it harder to know which assumption failed. In practice, this means asking the agent to make the smallest coherent change, run targeted validation, and expand only when the result supports it.\n\nSmall actions also protect team workflows. They reduce merge conflict risk, make pull requests easier to review, and help humans distinguish intentional product changes from incidental refactors.\n\n### Reliable Observability\n\nA loop is only as good as its observations. If the agent cannot run the relevant tests, see compiler output, inspect the UI, or read logs, it is operating partly blind. Good observability turns vague confidence into evidence.\n\nGood observability includes:\n\n* fast targeted tests for local feedback\n* type checks and lint checks for structural issues\n* build commands for integration confidence\n* runtime logs for behavioral debugging\n* screenshots or browser checks for UI work\n* code review comments for human judgment\n\n### Stopping Rules\n\nAgents need to know when to stop. Without stopping rules, an agent may keep polishing, refactor unrelated code, or chase diminishing returns. Stopping rules are especially important in shared repositories where user changes, generated files, credentials, and deployment actions can create risk.\n\nUseful stopping rules include:\n\n* stop when the requested behavior is implemented and validation passes\n* stop when a blocker requires missing credentials, data, or product judgment\n* stop before destructive commands unless explicitly approved\n* stop when the next step would affect unrelated user changes\n* stop when the remaining issue is outside the task scope\n\n## Common Loop Engineering Patterns For Software Teams\n\nLoop engineering shows up in many parts of software development because different tasks need different feedback signals. A compiler-driven migration, a runtime debugging session, and a product copy iteration all use loops, but they should not observe the same data or stop at the same point.\n\n### Test-Driven Agent Loop\n\nIn a test-driven loop, the agent starts by reproducing a failure or writing a failing test, then changes implementation code until the test passes. This pattern works well for bug fixes, parser behavior, data transformation logic, and regression prevention because the test gives the agent a clear pass/fail signal.\n\nThe loop is:\n\n1. reproduce or encode the expected behavior\n2. confirm the test fails for the right reason\n3. implement the smallest fix\n4. rerun the targeted test\n5. run broader validation if needed\n\n### Compiler-Driven Loop\n\nTyped languages create excellent feedback loops because the compiler can identify missing fields, incompatible types, unreachable branches, and invalid API usage. An agent can make a change, run the type checker, and use the resulting errors as a precise repair list.\n\nThis loop is especially useful during migrations, dependency upgrades, and refactors. The compiler does not prove the product is correct, but it quickly catches structural mistakes that would otherwise consume review time.\n\n### Review-Driven Loop\n\nIn a review-driven loop, human feedback becomes the observation source. A reviewer leaves comments, the agent categorizes them, makes changes where appropriate, responds to non-code feedback, and verifies the result. This pattern is useful because it keeps humans focused on judgment while the agent handles mechanical follow-through.\n\nReview-driven loops work best when comments are treated as requirements, not suggestions to blindly apply. The agent should distinguish bugs, product questions, style preferences, and out-of-scope requests before editing.\n\n### Runtime Debugging Loop\n\nSome failures only appear when the application runs. In a runtime loop, the agent uses logs, stack traces, HTTP responses, browser output, or reproduction steps to narrow the cause. The key is to keep each iteration evidence-based: form a hypothesis, make a targeted change or add a targeted inspection, observe the result, and update the hypothesis.\n\nFor frontend work, the observation might be a browser screenshot, a hydration error, or responsive layout behavior. For backend work, it might be a request trace, a database constraint error, or a queue retry log.\n\n### Product Iteration Loop\n\nNot every loop is purely technical. Product work often requires iteration through copy, UI states, edge cases, and acceptance criteria. The agent may implement a version, compare it against design constraints, adjust the layout, and verify responsive behavior.\n\nFor marketing pages and frontend work, the loop should include semantic HTML, metadata, accessibility, responsive checks, and brand consistency.\n\n## Loop Engineering For Development Teams\n\nLoop engineering becomes more important as teams adopt AI agents across more workflows. Individual developers can rely on personal judgment to stop an agent or redirect it. Teams need repeatable standards so agent behavior is predictable across repositories, people, and tasks.\n\nStrong team-level loop engineering often includes:\n\n* repository instructions that explain coding conventions and validation commands\n* branch and pull request rules for agent-generated changes\n* safe defaults around destructive commands and credentials\n* standard prompts for common work like bug fixes, migrations, and reviews\n* CI checks that agents and humans both trust\n* clear ownership for final product and architecture decisions\n\nThe goal is not to remove humans from engineering. The goal is to let humans spend more time on judgment, architecture, product quality, and review while agents handle more of the repetitive loop mechanics.\n\n### Loop Engineering Risks And Failure Modes\n\nPoorly designed loops can create real problems. The most common failure modes are predictable, and each one points back to a missing part of the loop.\n\n### Thrashing\n\nThrashing happens when an agent repeatedly changes code without converging. This often means the goal is unclear, the validation signal is noisy, or the agent is editing too much at once. The fix is to narrow the objective, reduce the diff size, and use a more reliable observation source.\n\nFor example, an agent that keeps changing both frontend state management and backend validation is harder to debug than an agent that first proves where the failure occurs.\n\n### Overfitting To Tests\n\nAn agent can make tests pass while missing the actual product requirement. This is especially common when tests are too narrow or the user-visible behavior is not checked.\n\nThe fix is to combine automated tests with requirement review and, where relevant, manual or browser-based verification.\n\n### Context Drift\n\nContext drift happens when the agent keeps working from stale assumptions. It may miss a user edit, ignore a new failure, or continue with a plan that no longer matches the code. The fix is to refresh context after meaningful observations and avoid treating the initial plan as sacred.\n\nThis is especially important in active branches where a human or another agent may be editing nearby files.\n\n### Unsafe Autonomy\n\nMore autonomy is not always better. Agents that can run destructive commands, rewrite unrelated files, or push changes without review can cause serious damage.\n\nThe fix is permissioning, scoped tools, human approval for risky actions, and clear stop conditions.\n\n## How Kilo Code Supports Loop Engineering Workflows\n\nKilo Code is built around the idea that AI coding should be iterative, inspectable, and flexible. It supports agent workflows that can explore a codebase, edit files, run commands, and use feedback to continue toward a verified result.\n\nSeveral parts of Kilo's approach matter for loop engineering:\n\n* **Multiple modes**: teams can separate coding, asking, debugging, planning, and custom workflows instead of forcing every task through one behavior.\n* **Model flexibility**: different loops benefit from different models. Some tasks need deeper reasoning, while others need speed or cost efficiency. Kilo supports [500+ hosted models](/leaderboard) and local model options.\n* **Open source foundation**: developers can inspect, adapt, and extend their AI coding environment instead of relying on a black box.\n* **Team-ready controls**: organizations can combine agent workflows with centralized billing, usage visibility, role-based access, and security practices.\n\nThose points matter because loop engineering is not only a model-quality problem. It is also a workflow-control problem. Teams need to decide which tasks require deeper reasoning, which tasks can use cheaper or faster models, which operations need approval, and which validation commands should run before a change is considered complete.\n\nThe same principle applies to cost and model selection. A long debugging loop can consume many model calls, while a quick copy edit may not need a frontier reasoning model. Model flexibility helps teams match the loop to the task instead of routing every workflow through the same cost and latency profile.\n\nFor a broader foundation, read [What Is an AI Coding Agent?](/articles/what-is-an-ai-coding-agent) or compare tools in the [AI coding assistant buyer's guide](/articles/ai-coding-assistant-buyers-guide).\n\n### Loop Engineering Videos And Further Watching\n\nLoop engineering is still an emerging term, so many useful videos discuss it through adjacent concepts like agentic coding, plan-act-verify loops, self-correcting agents, and AI coding feedback loops. These YouTube searches are good starting points:\n\n* [Loop engineering for AI coding](https://www.youtube.com/results?search_query=loop+engineering+ai+coding)\n* [AI coding agent feedback loops](https://www.youtube.com/results?search_query=ai+coding+agent+feedback+loop)\n* [Agentic coding workflows](https://www.youtube.com/results?search_query=agentic+coding+workflow)\n* [Plan act verify AI agents](https://www.youtube.com/results?search_query=plan+act+verify+ai+agents)\n* [Self-correcting AI coding agents](https://www.youtube.com/results?search_query=self+correcting+ai+coding+agent)\n\n## Best Practices For Designing AI Coding Loops\n\nThe best way to introduce loop engineering is to start with small, repeatable workflows and make the feedback signal explicit. Teams do not need to redesign every engineering process at once. They can begin with bug fixes, test repair, dependency upgrades, or pull request comment resolution, then standardize the loops that work.\n\n### Start With A Narrow Task\n\nAsk for one coherent outcome at a time. \"Add account deletion\" is better than \"improve settings.\" \"Fix the failing checkout tax calculation test\" is better than \"debug checkout.\" Narrow tasks make it easier for the agent to know which files matter and which validation output is relevant.\n\n### Tell The Agent How To Verify Work\n\nIf you know the right command, include it. If you know a specific browser path, API endpoint, or acceptance scenario, include that too. Verification instructions turn vague progress into measurable progress. They also reduce the chance that the agent stops after code generation without checking the result.\n\n### Prefer Existing Patterns\n\nGood loops respect the codebase. The agent should inspect nearby implementations, reuse shared components, follow existing naming, and avoid adding new abstractions unless the task needs them. This keeps the feedback loop grounded in the project rather than in generic examples.\n\n### Keep Humans In The Judgment Seat\n\nAgents can execute loops quickly, but humans still own product intent, risk tolerance, architecture, and final review. The strongest workflows combine agent iteration with human judgment at the right checkpoints. A good rule is to automate evidence gathering and mechanical repair while reserving product and architecture decisions for people.\n\n### Capture Reusable Loops\n\nWhen a workflow works well, turn it into a repeatable pattern. A team might define standard loops for dependency upgrades, incident fixes, PR comment resolution, UI polish, and test repair. Reusable loops reduce onboarding friction because developers do not have to reinvent prompts, validation commands, and stopping rules for every task.\n\n### The Future Of Loop Engineering\n\nAs coding agents improve, the most important skill will not be writing the perfect one-line prompt. It will be designing reliable systems of context, action, observation, and correction.\n\nLoop engineering is likely to become a normal part of software engineering practice. Teams will evaluate AI coding tools not only by model quality, but by how well they support safe iteration, repository awareness, validation, review, and team governance.\n\nThe best agents will not simply generate more code. They will help developers close better loops.\n\n## FAQ\n\n### What is loop engineering?\n\nLoop engineering is the practice of designing AI-assisted workflows where an agent repeatedly plans, acts, observes feedback, and adjusts until a software task is complete or blocked.\n\n### How is loop engineering different from prompt engineering?\n\nPrompt engineering focuses on the input given to a model. Loop engineering focuses on the full iterative system around the model, including tools, context, validation, feedback, and stopping rules.\n\n### Why does loop engineering matter for AI coding agents?\n\nAI coding agents work on real repositories with changing context and uncertain requirements. Loop engineering helps them use tests, type checks, logs, diffs, and human feedback to make verified progress instead of relying on a single generated answer.\n\n### What is an example of a coding loop?\n\nA common coding loop is: inspect the relevant files, make a small change, run a targeted test, read the failure or success output, adjust the code, and repeat until the task passes validation.\n\n### Can loop engineering be used without AI agents?\n\nYes. Developers already use feedback loops through tests, compilers, code review, and debugging. AI agents make loop design more explicit because the system can automate more steps in the cycle.\n\n### What makes a loop safe?\n\nA safe loop has clear scope, small reversible changes, reliable validation, human approval for risky actions, and explicit stopping rules for blockers or destructive operations."}], "response_time": 1.99, "request_id": "0f973f7f-59e0-44c6-a287-4d964f5e9caf"}